NOMINAL ENCODING: 
	• It does not have any order(in simple terms we don't need to worry on orders)
	• Ex: Gender, state.

In nominal encoding we have more types: 
	1. One-hot encoding.
	2. One-hot encoding with many categorical variable.
	3. Mean Encoding .
	4. Count or frequency encoding. 






One-hot Encoding:
	• One hot encoding basically used for nominal data types. 
	• If you have only small number of features, then use it otherwise use 2nd type.
	

	• The main thing is that it will increase the number of features, so we can do, drop any one feature in the dataset.  
	• That is called Dummy Variable trap. 
	• Dummy variable trap also causes the curse of dimensionality.



One-hot Encoding with multiple category variables:
	• If we have just 2 to 3 features means we can apply the one hot encoding.
	• If we have more than 10 to 20 features means we use the one hot encoding with multi cat.


	• What we are going to do means we are going to take first 10 to 20 repeated features and do the one hot encoding. 
	• It's a proven method. So we can.


	
	
	
COUNT OR FREQUENCY ENCODING:
	• When we use this - whenever we have the high number of categorical data In our dataset we can use this method.
	• The more number of labels in the data set is called HIGH CARDINALITY.
Advantages: 
	• Easy to implement.
	• Prevent from curse of dimensionality.
Dis:
	• If the two values are same it lose the valuable information.

